    slug: "parenting-capacity-assessment-a-solicitors-guide",
    title: "Parenting Capacity Assessment: A Solicitor's Guide",
    excerpt: "A comprehensive guide to parenting capacity assessments in care proceedings — what they assess, who should carry them out, what the report covers, and how to instruct effectively.",
    content: `<h2>What Is a Parenting Capacity Assessment?</h2>
<p>A parenting capacity assessment (PCA) is a specialist evaluation conducted by an expert — typically a chartered clinical or forensic psychologist, or in some cases a consultant psychiatrist — to assess a parent's or carer's ability to meet their child's needs both now and in the future. PCAs are most commonly commissioned in care proceedings under the Children Act 1989, where the local authority is applying for a care or supervision order.</p>
<p>The central question in care proceedings is whether the threshold criteria under s.31 of the Children Act 1989 are met, and if so, what order is in the child's best interests. A parenting capacity assessment directly informs the second question: can this parent safely care for their child with support, or does the risk to the child's welfare necessitate removal?</p>

<h2>What Does a Parenting Capacity Assessment Cover?</h2>
<p>The precise scope is defined by the letter of instruction, but a thorough PCA typically addresses:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Parenting history and background:</strong> The parent's own childhood experiences, attachment history, relationship history, and previous involvement with children's services.</li>
  <li><strong>Current mental health and psychological functioning:</strong> Diagnosis of any mental health conditions, personality functioning, substance misuse, and the impact of these on parenting.</li>
  <li><strong>Understanding of the child's needs:</strong> Whether the parent has insight into the concerns identified by the local authority and can prioritise the child's needs over their own.</li>
  <li><strong>Capacity to change:</strong> A forward-looking opinion on the parent's ability to make and sustain changes within a timeframe that is in the child's best interests.</li>
  <li><strong>Risk of harm:</strong> An assessment of the risk that the child will suffer significant harm if returned to or remaining in the parent's care.</li>
  <li><strong>Recommendations:</strong> Whether the expert recommends rehabilitation, supported contact, or an alternative placement, and what interventions — if any — could address identified deficits.</li>
</ul>
<p>In some cases, the assessment extends to include observations of parent-child interaction, particularly where attachment quality is in question.</p>

<h2>Who Should Conduct the Assessment?</h2>
<p>Parenting capacity assessments require considerable expertise. The expert must have:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Specialist training in child development, attachment theory, and trauma</li>
  <li>Experience of working with families in child protection contexts</li>
  <li>Competence in using validated psychometric tools (e.g., Adult Attachment Interview, Child Abuse Potential Inventory)</li>
  <li>Understanding of the legal framework and the questions courts need answered</li>
  <li>Experience of withstanding cross-examination in the Family Court</li>
</ul>
<p>Courts and CAFCASS guardians are increasingly attuned to the difference between a well-evidenced, independently formed opinion and a report that reflects the assumptions of the instructing party. The expert's independence and willingness to give an honest — even unfavourable — opinion is essential.</p>

<h2>The 26-Week Timetable and Early Instruction</h2>
<p>In public law proceedings, the court must resolve matters within 26 weeks unless there are exceptional circumstances. This timetable is tight, and expert evidence is one of the most common reasons for extensions. An application for leave to instruct an expert under FPR 25.4 must be made as early as possible — ideally at the Case Management Hearing (CMH).</p>
<p>Practitioners should be aware that finding an expert of appropriate calibre who is available within the timetable can be challenging. We strongly recommend making contact with providers early in proceedings, even before the CMH, to check availability and agree a timetable that works within the court's directions.</p>

<h2>Joint Instruction</h2>
<p>In the majority of family proceedings, parenting capacity assessments are jointly instructed by the parties (local authority, parents' solicitors, and the children's guardian). All parties contribute questions to the letter of instruction, and the expert is instructed to assist the court — not any single party. The jointly instructed expert's report is then available to all parties.</p>
<p>Where parties cannot agree on a joint expert, the court may direct the appointment of a single joint expert. In contested cases, it is rare for the court to permit each party to instruct their own expert in relation to parenting capacity.</p>

<h2>What Happens After the Report?</h2>
<p>Once the report is received, parties may submit written questions under FPR 25.9. The expert must respond within 28 days. In contested hearings, the expert will often give oral evidence before the judge and be cross-examined on their findings and methodology. Experts instructed through Psychology Direct are experienced in giving oral evidence and can assist solicitors in preparing for cross-examination by flagging the aspects of their opinion most likely to be challenged.</p>

<h2>Instructing Psychology Direct for Parenting Capacity Assessments</h2>
<p>We have extensive experience in providing parenting capacity assessments in public law proceedings across England and Wales. Our experts include chartered clinical psychologists with specialist expertise in child development, trauma, and family systems, as well as consultant psychiatrists where dual assessment is required.</p>
<p>We understand the pressures of the 26-week timetable and manage the process proactively — chasing appointments, tracking deadlines, and flagging potential slippage before it becomes a problem.</p>
<p>To discuss a potential instruction or check availability, please <a href="/contact/">contact our team</a>. We are happy to advise on the appropriate scope of assessment and assist with drafting questions for the letter of instruction.</p>`,
