    slug: "the-ehcp-process-explained-step-by-step-guide",
    title: "The EHCP Process Explained: A Step-by-Step Guide",
    excerpt: "From initial request to final plan, this step-by-step guide explains the Education, Health and Care Plan process — timelines, rights, and what to expect at each stage.",
    content: `<h2>What Is an EHCP?</h2>
<p>An Education, Health and Care Plan (EHCP) is a legally binding document produced by a local authority that describes a child or young person's special educational needs (SEN) and the provision that must be made to meet them. EHCPs replaced Statements of Special Educational Needs in September 2014 under the Children and Families Act 2014 and the SEND Code of Practice 2015.</p>
<p>EHCPs can cover children and young people from birth to age 25, and they integrate education, health, and social care needs in a single document — hence the name. Once issued, the EHCP places a legal duty on the local authority (and in some cases the school or college) to arrange the provision described.</p>

<h2>Step 1: Requesting an EHC Needs Assessment</h2>
<p>The process begins with a request for an Education, Health and Care Needs Assessment. This can be made by:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The child's parent or the young person themselves (if aged 16–25)</li>
  <li>The child's school, nursery, or college</li>
  <li>A health or social care professional</li>
  <li>Anyone else who considers an assessment may be necessary</li>
</ul>
<p>The local authority must decide within <strong>6 weeks</strong> whether to carry out the assessment. If they decline, they must give reasons, and the family has the right to appeal to the SEND Tribunal.</p>

<h2>Step 2: The EHC Needs Assessment</h2>
<p>If the local authority agrees to assess, it will gather information from a range of sources, including:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The child's school or educational setting</li>
  <li>The child's GP, paediatrician, or other health professionals</li>
  <li>Social care (if applicable)</li>
  <li>The child and their parents</li>
  <li>Any independent professional reports the family has obtained</li>
</ul>
<p>This is the stage at which an independent Educational Psychologist assessment may be commissioned — either by the local authority or privately by the family. The EP assessment is typically one of the most important pieces of evidence in the process, as it provides a detailed picture of the child's cognitive profile, learning needs, and recommended provision.</p>

<h2>Step 3: The Decision to Issue an EHCP</h2>
<p>Within <strong>16 weeks</strong> of the initial request, the local authority must decide whether to issue an EHCP. If it decides not to, families can appeal.</p>
<p>If it decides to issue a plan, it must send a draft EHCP to the family and the child's school for comment. The family has at least 15 days to respond.</p>

<h2>Step 4: The Draft EHCP</h2>
<p>The draft EHCP must set out:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Section A:</strong> The child's aspirations and interests</li>
  <li><strong>Section B:</strong> The child's special educational needs</li>
  <li><strong>Section C:</strong> The child's health needs related to their SEN</li>
  <li><strong>Section D:</strong> The child's social care needs related to their SEN</li>
  <li><strong>Section E:</strong> Outcomes — what the child is expected to achieve</li>
  <li><strong>Section F:</strong> Educational provision — the specific, quantified support the child must receive</li>
  <li><strong>Section G:</strong> Health provision</li>
  <li><strong>Section H:</strong> Social care provision</li>
  <li><strong>Section I:</strong> The name and type of educational placement</li>
</ul>
<p>Section F is critically important. Provision must be specific and quantified — vague language such as "regular support" is insufficient. Families should check that every need identified in Section B has corresponding provision in Section F.</p>

<h2>Step 5: School Preference</h2>
<p>Families have the right to request a particular school — mainstream or special — to be named in Section I. The local authority must name the requested school unless it would be unsuitable for the child, incompatible with the efficient education of others, or an inefficient use of resources. Disagreements over school placement are one of the most common grounds for SEND Tribunal appeals.</p>

<h2>Step 6: The Final EHCP</h2>
<p>The final EHCP must be issued within <strong>20 weeks</strong> of the original request for assessment. Once finalised, it is legally binding. The named school or provision must deliver what is specified in Section F.</p>

<h2>Annual Reviews</h2>
<p>EHCPs must be reviewed at least annually. The review checks whether the plan remains appropriate, whether outcomes are being achieved, and whether any changes to provision are needed. During school transitions (e.g., primary to secondary, secondary to post-16), enhanced reviews take place to prepare the updated plan.</p>

<h2>Independent Educational Psychologist Assessments</h2>
<p>Families sometimes commission an independent EP assessment when they are dissatisfied with the local authority's assessment, when the LA has refused to assess, or when they want robust independent evidence for a SEND Tribunal appeal. An independent assessment can also be valuable in preparation for an annual review where families believe provision needs to be significantly changed.</p>
<p><a href="/education/ehcp-assessments/">Psychology Direct provides independent EHCP assessments</a> across England. Our educational psychologists produce thorough, evidence-based reports that comply with EHCP requirements and are written to be useful both to families and to the SEND Tribunal where needed.</p>
<p>If you would like to discuss commissioning an independent EP assessment, please <a href="/contact/">contact our team</a>.</p>`,
