    id: "wp57",
    slug: "ep-assessments-dyslexia-adhd-dyscalculia-what-schools-need-to-know",
    title: "EP Assessments for Dyslexia, ADHD and Dyscalculia: What Schools Need to Know",
    excerpt: "Educational psychology assessments are the gold standard for identifying specific learning difficulties. This guide explains what EP assessments cover for dyslexia, ADHD, and dyscalculia.",
    content: `<h2>Why EP Assessments Matter for Specific Learning Difficulties</h2>
<p>Specific learning difficulties — including dyslexia, ADHD (in its educational context), and dyscalculia — affect a significant proportion of school-age children and can have a profound impact on academic attainment, self-esteem, and long-term outcomes if not identified and supported appropriately.</p>
<p>An educational psychology (EP) assessment provides the most comprehensive and evidence-based picture of a child's cognitive profile, learning strengths and difficulties, and support needs. For many children, an EP assessment is the gateway to appropriate specialist provision — whether through an EHCP, targeted in-school support, access arrangements, or specialist teaching.</p>

<h2>Assessing Dyslexia</h2>
<p>Dyslexia is the most prevalent specific learning difficulty. It is characterised by difficulties with accurate and/or fluent word reading and decoding, poor spelling, and difficulties with phonological processing — despite adequate intelligence and conventional teaching.</p>
<p>An EP assessment for dyslexia typically includes:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Cognitive ability:</strong> Verbal comprehension, perceptual reasoning, and fluid reasoning assessed using standardised tools such as the WISC-V or WRIT.</li>
  <li><strong>Phonological processing:</strong> Phonological awareness, phonological memory, and rapid automatised naming — the three core deficits associated with dyslexia (Frith's three-level framework).</li>
  <li><strong>Reading:</strong> Accuracy, fluency, and comprehension using standardised tests (e.g., WIAT-III UK, YARC, NARA).</li>
  <li><strong>Spelling:</strong> Accuracy across age-appropriate word lists.</li>
  <li><strong>Writing speed and quality.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Working memory and processing speed:</strong> Often significantly affected in dyslexic learners.</li>
</ul>
<p>Following assessment, the EP produces a detailed report including a formulation of the child's profile, a diagnosis of dyslexia (where appropriate), and specific, evidence-based recommendations for school support, specialist teaching, and any access arrangements required.</p>

<h2>Assessing ADHD — The Educational Perspective</h2>
<p>It is important to note that a formal diagnosis of ADHD is a medical diagnosis, made by a psychiatrist or paediatrician. Educational psychologists do not diagnose ADHD. However, they play a crucial role in:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Assessing the educational and cognitive impact of ADHD — how attention, working memory, and executive function difficulties affect learning</li>
  <li>Distinguishing between ADHD-related difficulties and other explanations for inattention or impulsivity (e.g., anxiety, dyslexia, sensory processing differences)</li>
  <li>Providing evidence to support a referral to a paediatrician or CAMHS for formal assessment</li>
  <li>Recommending classroom strategies and environmental adjustments</li>
  <li>Informing access arrangements applications where ADHD has been formally diagnosed</li>
</ul>
<p>An EP assessment for ADHD concerns typically includes rating scales completed by parents and teachers (e.g., Conners 3, SNAP-IV), observation in the classroom, and standardised assessment of executive function and attention. This forms part of the holistic picture for both diagnostic and support planning purposes.</p>

<h2>Assessing Dyscalculia</h2>
<p>Dyscalculia is a specific learning difficulty affecting mathematical ability. It is less well understood than dyslexia, but the evidence base is growing. Children with dyscalculia have persistent difficulties with number sense, arithmetical facts, and mathematical reasoning that are disproportionate to their general ability.</p>
<p>An EP assessment for dyscalculia includes:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Standardised mathematical ability assessments (e.g., WIAT-III Maths subtests, Dyscalculia Screener)</li>
  <li>Assessment of number sense and subitising</li>
  <li>Working memory assessment — particularly for numerical information</li>
  <li>Comparison of mathematical performance with reading, language, and general cognitive ability</li>
</ul>
<p>Dyscalculia is frequently co-occurring with dyslexia and ADHD. A comprehensive EP assessment will identify the full profile of difficulties and make recommendations accordingly.</p>

<h2>What Schools Should Do</h2>
<p>Referral for an EP assessment should follow a period of concern, monitoring, and in-school intervention. Schools should:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Identify concerns early, supported by teacher observation, screening tools, and review of attainment data</li>
  <li>Implement and document targeted interventions in line with the graduated approach (assess, plan, do, review)</li>
  <li>Involve parents in discussions about the child's needs</li>
  <li>Refer to the EP when the child's needs are not being met despite appropriate intervention, or when a more detailed assessment is needed to guide next steps</li>
</ol>
<p>A well-timed EP referral avoids the trap of labelling too early or too late. It also means the school can demonstrate to parents and the SEND Tribunal, if necessary, that they followed a structured, evidence-based process.</p>

<h2>EP Assessments from Psychology Direct</h2>
<p><a href="/education/">Psychology Direct provides independent EP assessments</a> for dyslexia, ADHD (educational impact), dyscalculia, and other specific learning difficulties. We work directly with schools, MATs, and local authorities across England, providing fast turnaround and reports written to the standard required for EHCP and JCQ purposes.</p>
<p>To discuss referral criteria or commission an assessment, please <a href="/contact/">contact our team</a>.</p>`,
