    title: "The SEND Code of Practice 2015: What Schools Must Do",
    excerpt: "The SEND Code of Practice 2015 sets out the statutory framework for supporting children with special educational needs and disability. This guide explains the key duties for schools.",
    content: `<h2>What Is the SEND Code of Practice?</h2>
<p>The Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) Code of Practice: 0 to 25 years was published in 2015, following the Children and Families Act 2014. It sets out the statutory guidance that local authorities, schools, colleges, and health and care services must have regard to when supporting children and young people with special educational needs and disabilities.</p>
<p>"Must have regard to" means that these organisations must follow the Code unless they have good reason not to, and must be prepared to justify any deviation. In practice, the Code effectively defines minimum standards for SEND support across the system.</p>

<h2>The Four Areas of Need</h2>
<p>The Code of Practice identifies four broad areas of need that help professionals understand and describe children's SEND:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Communication and interaction:</strong> Including speech, language and communication needs, and autism spectrum condition.</li>
  <li><strong>Cognition and learning:</strong> Including specific learning difficulties (dyslexia, dyscalculia, dyspraxia), moderate learning difficulties, and severe or profound learning difficulties.</li>
  <li><strong>Social, emotional, and mental health difficulties:</strong> Including anxiety, depression, ADHD, attachment difficulties, and self-harm.</li>
  <li><strong>Sensory and/or physical needs:</strong> Including visual impairment, hearing impairment, and physical disability.</li>
</ul>
<p>Children often have needs across more than one area. The Code emphasises that needs should be understood holistically, not reduced to a single label.</p>

<h2>The Graduated Approach: Assess, Plan, Do, Review</h2>
<p>The central mechanism through which schools must support pupils with SEND is the graduated approach — a four-stage cycle of:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Assess:</strong> The school carries out an analysis of the pupil's needs, drawing on teacher assessments, attainment data, parental input, and — where appropriate — specialist assessments.</li>
  <li><strong>Plan:</strong> The school agrees a plan with parents, setting out the adjustments, interventions, and support to be put in place, along with expected outcomes and a review date.</li>
  <li><strong>Do:</strong> The planned support is implemented. The class teacher remains responsible for the pupil's progress and quality of teaching.</li>
  <li><strong>Review:</strong> The effectiveness of the support is reviewed. Where a pupil is not making adequate progress, the school must consider whether a more intensive intervention, specialist assessment, or referral for an EHCP needs assessment is appropriate.</li>
</ol>
<p>This cycle underpins all SEND support at SEN Support level (formerly "School Action" and "School Action Plus"). Documentation of the graduated approach is essential — both for the pupil's benefit and as a record that demonstrates the school's duty of care if challenged.</p>

<h2>The Role of the SENCO</h2>
<p>All mainstream schools must have a designated Special Educational Needs Co-ordinator (SENCO). The SENCO must be a qualified teacher, and since 2009 newly appointed SENCOs in maintained schools have been required to obtain the National Award for SEN Co-ordination (NASENCo) within three years of appointment.</p>
<p>The SENCO's responsibilities include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Overseeing day-to-day operation of the school's SEND policy</li>
  <li>Co-ordinating provision for children with SEND</li>
  <li>Advising class and subject teachers</li>
  <li>Managing EHCPs and liaison with external agencies</li>
  <li>Contributing to the school's SEND information report</li>
</ul>

<h2>The SEND Information Report</h2>
<p>All maintained schools and academies must publish a SEND Information Report on their website, updated annually. This must describe the school's approach to identifying, assessing, and supporting pupils with SEND, including how parents can raise concerns and how the school works with external agencies. Failure to publish or update the report is a breach of statutory duty and is increasingly monitored by Ofsted.</p>

<h2>Local Offer</h2>
<p>Local authorities must publish a "Local Offer" — a comprehensive description of the support available locally for children and young people with SEND aged 0–25. Schools must be actively involved in contributing to and shaping the Local Offer, and must publish their provision in a form that parents can access. The Local Offer is an important resource for families navigating the SEND system.</p>

<h2>When Should Schools Seek EP Input?</h2>
<p>The Code of Practice is clear that schools should seek specialist external advice when a pupil's needs are not being met through the graduated approach, or when a more detailed assessment is needed to inform planning. Educational psychologists are among the key specialists schools should consult.</p>
<p>Common triggers for EP referral include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Persistent lack of progress despite well-targeted interventions</li>
  <li>Complex or unclear presentation requiring specialist assessment</li>
  <li>Consideration of whether an EHCP needs assessment is appropriate</li>
  <li>SEND Tribunal proceedings where independent evidence is needed</li>
  <li>Transition planning (primary to secondary, secondary to post-16)</li>
</ul>

<h2>How Psychology Direct Supports Schools</h2>
<p><a href="/education/schools-academies-colleges/">Psychology Direct works directly with schools, academies, and colleges</a> to provide educational psychology assessments, SENCO consultancy, and specialist assessment services. Our educational psychologists are experienced in working within the SEND Code of Practice framework and producing reports that support schools' compliance with their statutory duties.</p>
<p>We provide assessments for EHCP purposes, access arrangements, and specialist learning difficulty assessments. To discuss commissioning our services, please <a href="/contact/">contact our team</a>.</p>`,
