    slug: "how-to-write-a-strong-cv-for-expert-witness-work",
    title: "How to Write a Strong CV for Expert Witness Work",
    excerpt: "Your CV is often the first thing a solicitor sees when considering whether to instruct you. This guide explains how to structure a medico-legal CV that wins instructions.",
    content: `<h2>Why Your CV Matters More Than You Might Think</h2>
<p>When a solicitor is looking for an expert witness, they are making a risk decision. They are choosing someone to whom they will entrust part of their client's case, and whose evidence they will stake their professional credibility on. Your CV is usually the first thing they see — and often the deciding factor between being shortlisted or passed over.</p>
<p>A clinical or academic CV is structured around what you have done in your career. A medico-legal CV is structured around why a solicitor should trust you to help their client in court. These are very different documents, and psychologists and psychiatrists who are new to expert witness work frequently present themselves poorly on paper as a result.</p>

<h2>The Key Sections of a Medico-Legal CV</h2>
<h3>1. Professional header</h3>
<p>Include your full name, qualifications (listed after your name — e.g., DClinPsy, CPsychol, AFBPsS), HCPC registration number, and direct contact details. Include a brief statement (2–3 sentences) describing your area of expertise and the types of instruction you accept. Solicitors scan CVs quickly — make it immediately clear who you are and what you do.</p>

<h3>2. Areas of expertise</h3>
<p>List the specific types of case you are competent to assess. Be precise. "Expert witness experience across a range of cases" is unhelpful. Instead: "Specialist in PTSD assessment in personal injury and clinical negligence cases; parenting capacity assessments in public law proceedings; risk assessment for the Parole Board." Solicitors often search by specialism — make it easy to find you.</p>

<h3>3. Qualifications and training</h3>
<p>Include your core qualifications in reverse chronological order, then any medico-legal specific training. Relevant courses include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Bond Solon Expert Witness training (a standard marker of seriousness in the medico-legal sector)</li>
  <li>Expert Witness Institute (EWI) membership or accreditation</li>
  <li>CSAB (Cardiff and Vale University Health Board) or similar medico-legal report writing courses</li>
  <li>CPD in specific areas (e.g., risk assessment tools such as HCR-20, PCL-R, RM2000)</li>
</ul>

<h3>4. Registration and accreditation</h3>
<p>State your HCPC registration (mandatory), your BPS chartered status, and any specialist division membership (e.g., Division of Forensic Psychology, Division of Clinical Psychology). If you are a consultant psychiatrist, your GMC registration and Royal College of Psychiatrists fellowship are the relevant credentials.</p>

<h3>5. Medico-legal experience</h3>
<p>This is the section most psychologists and psychiatrists undervalue. Solicitors want to know:</p>
<ul>
  <li>How many medico-legal reports have you produced? (Give an approximate number or range, e.g., "approximately 150 reports over 8 years")</li>
  <li>In which courts and tribunals have you given evidence? (County Court, Crown Court, Family Court, Employment Tribunal, Immigration Tribunal, Upper Tribunal, Court of Protection, etc.)</li>
  <li>Have you been tested in cross-examination? Have you ever been criticised by a judge? (Honesty here is valued — every experienced expert has had challenging moments in court)</li>
  <li>Which types of proceedings are you most experienced in?</li>
</ul>
<p>Do not conflate clinical report writing with medico-legal report writing. A GP discharge summary is not a medico-legal report. Be clear about what you mean.</p>

<h3>6. Academic and research background</h3>
<p>Relevant publications, research experience, and academic appointments can strengthen your credibility, particularly in complex cases where methodology may be challenged. Include any publications relevant to your area of expert witness work. A publication on trauma psychology is far more relevant than a paper on unrelated clinical topics.</p>

<h3>7. Clinical background</h3>
<p>A brief summary of your clinical career demonstrates the depth of your practical experience. Solicitors want to know you have genuinely worked with the population about whom you are offering opinion evidence. An expert who has spent their career in a closely related clinical role is generally more credible than one who has moved to expert witness work from a primarily research or management background.</p>

<h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Too long:</strong> A medico-legal CV should be 2–3 pages maximum. Solicitors will not read 10 pages.</li>
  <li><strong>Burying the medico-legal experience:</strong> This should be prominently positioned, not hidden at the end after a long academic publication list.</li>
  <li><strong>Vague claims:</strong> "Extensive court experience" tells a solicitor nothing. Give specifics.</li>
  <li><strong>No mention of areas you will not accept:</strong> It is perfectly acceptable — and helpful — to note the types of case you do not take (e.g., "I do not accept instructions in cases involving complex psychiatric medication management" if you are a psychologist).</li>
  <li><strong>Outdated CV:</strong> A CV that has not been updated in five years raises questions about whether your medico-legal practice is still active.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Joining a Managed Expert Panel</h2>
<p>One of the most effective ways to build a medico-legal practice is to join a reputable managed expert panel. Providers like <a href="/about/">Psychology Direct</a> receive instructions from solicitors across the country and allocate cases to panel members based on specialism, experience, and availability. Joining a panel gives you access to a steady flow of instructions and the administrative support needed to manage a practice effectively.</p>
<p>If you are interested in joining our panel of associate psychologists and psychiatrists, please <a href="/contact/">get in touch</a>. We work with professionals at all stages of their medico-legal career, from those taking their first instructions to highly experienced court witnesses.</p>`,
