    id: "wp60",
    slug: "medico-legal-reports-format-structure-best-practice",
    title: "Medico-Legal Reports: Format, Structure and Best Practice",
    excerpt: "A well-structured medico-legal report is the foundation of effective expert evidence. This guide explains the expected format, common structural errors, and how to produce reports that courts trust.",
    content: `<h2>Why Report Quality Matters</h2>
<p>The medico-legal report is your primary contribution to legal proceedings. It will be read by solicitors, barristers, judges, and — in some proceedings — lay tribunal members. It may be the basis for cross-examination lasting several hours. A poorly structured, inadequately evidenced, or internally inconsistent report can undermine your credibility, harm the client's case, and in the most serious cases attract judicial criticism that follows you throughout your career.</p>
<p>Conversely, a well-written report — one that is logical, evidence-based, clear, and honest — builds your reputation rapidly. Solicitors and barristers have long memories for experts who produce reliable, court-ready work.</p>

<h2>The Required Structure</h2>
<p>The precise structure required varies between jurisdictions and proceedings, but a compliant medico-legal report in England and Wales will typically include all of the following sections.</p>

<h3>1. Title page</h3>
<p>Include the case name, court reference (if known), your full name and qualifications, the date of the report, and a clear statement that the report is prepared for the purpose of legal proceedings.</p>

<h3>2. Summary of instructions</h3>
<p>State who instructed you, when you were instructed, and the specific questions you were asked to address. This section ensures the court and parties understand the scope of your instructions and flags if any questions have not been answered (and why).</p>

<h3>3. Documents considered</h3>
<p>List every document you were provided with and considered. If you were not provided with documents that you consider relevant to your opinion, note this — it may affect the weight the court gives to your evidence.</p>

<h3>4. Background and history</h3>
<p>Provide a factual account of the relevant history as you have been able to establish it from the documents and the assessment. Be careful to distinguish clearly between what the subject reported to you and what is recorded in objective documentation. Disputes about historical facts are for the court to resolve — your role is to record what you have been told and found, not to adjudicate on credibility.</p>

<h3>5. Assessment findings</h3>
<p>Describe the assessment you conducted — the setting, duration, and any tests or assessment tools used. Provide a mental state examination or psychological test findings in sufficient detail for the reader to understand the basis for your clinical observations. Name and reference all standardised tools used, and provide normative data (standard scores, percentiles) for any psychometric tests administered.</p>

<h3>6. Opinion</h3>
<p>This is the section the court will focus on. Your opinion should:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Address each of the questions posed in your letter of instruction in turn</li>
  <li>Be expressed in terms of the appropriate evidential standard (on the balance of probabilities in civil proceedings; beyond reasonable doubt is not your task)</li>
  <li>Distinguish between what you are able to say with confidence and where there is genuine uncertainty</li>
  <li>Acknowledge the limitations of your opinion where they exist</li>
  <li>Avoid straying into legal conclusions — you can opine on diagnosis, causation, and prognosis, but not on liability or quantum</li>
</ul>

<h3>7. Conclusion / summary</h3>
<p>A brief summary of the key points in your opinion is helpful, particularly in complex reports. Keep it factual and consistent with the body of the report — inconsistencies between the summary and the detailed opinion are a common source of cross-examination.</p>

<h3>8. Declaration and statement of truth</h3>
<p>The report must end with a statement of truth in the form required by the relevant procedural rules. For civil proceedings (CPR Part 35.3), the declaration must include: "I confirm that I have made clear which facts and matters referred to in this report are within my own knowledge and which are not. Those that are within my own knowledge I confirm to be true. The opinions I have expressed represent my true and complete professional opinion on the matters to which they refer."</p>
<p>In family proceedings (FPR Part 25), the declaration must also confirm that the expert understands their duty to the court and has complied with it.</p>

<h2>Common Errors That Draw Judicial Criticism</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Advocacy:</strong> Writing as though you are on the claimant's or defendant's side rather than providing an independent opinion.</li>
  <li><strong>Selective use of evidence:</strong> Relying on evidence that supports one conclusion while failing to engage with contradictory evidence.</li>
  <li><strong>Overstating certainty:</strong> Expressing opinions as definitive facts when they are, by nature, probabilistic.</li>
  <li><strong>Failing to address contrary opinions:</strong> If a different expert has reached a different conclusion, explain why you disagree — or, if their evidence has caused you to modify your view, say so.</li>
  <li><strong>Poor referencing:</strong> Citing diagnostic criteria, research, or guidelines without proper attribution.</li>
  <li><strong>Inconsistency:</strong> Stating one thing in the body of the report and something different in the conclusion.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Working with Psychology Direct</h2>
<p>Psychology Direct provides <a href="/expert-witness/process/">comprehensive administrative support</a> for experts working within our panel, including guidance on report structure, quality assurance review, and assistance with supplementary questions. We work with experts at all stages of their medico-legal career.</p>
<p>If you are interested in working with us as an associate expert, or would like to commission a report from our panel, please <a href="/contact/">contact our team</a>.</p>`,
